REST API stands for Representational State Transfer Application Programming Interface.
It is used for communication between client and server applications through the internet using the HTTP protocol.
In REST API, data or objects are treated as resources, and each resource is identified using a URL.

The client sends a request to the server using HTTP methods like:
GET → Read data
POST → Create data
PUT → Update data
DELETE → Remove data

REST APIs are stateless, meaning every request is independent and the server does not store client information between requests.
REST APIs usually send and receive data in JSON format because it is lightweight and easy to understand.

They are widely used in:
Web applications
Mobile applications
Microservices
Cloud applications

Example:
GET /employees/101
This request fetches employee details whose id is 101.

============================================================

HTTP and HTTPS are protocols used to transfer data between a client (browser/app) and a server.
**********HTTP************
HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)
Data is transferred in plain text.
Not secure because hackers can read or modify the data.
Used for normal, non-sensitive communication.
Default port number is 80.
URL starts with:
http://

Example:
http://example.com

*******HTTPS******************
HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure)
HTTPS is the secure version of HTTP.
Data is encrypted using SSL/TLS certificates.
Prevents hacking, data theft, and tampering.
Used for banking, login pages, payment systems, etc.
Default port number is 443.
URL starts with:
https://

Example:
https://example.com


================
How we can secure REST APIs
We can secure REST APIs using the following methods:

1. HTTPS
Use HTTPS instead of HTTP to encrypt data during communication between client and server.

2. Authentication
Verify the identity of the user before allowing access.
Common authentication methods:
JWT Token Authentication
OAuth 2.0
Basic Authentication

3. Authorization
Check whether the user has permission to access a particular resource or API.

Example:
Admin can delete users
Normal user cannot delete users

4. JWT Token
After successful login, the server generates a token.
The client sends this token in every request.

Example:
Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOi...

5. Input Validation
Validate request data to prevent:

SQL Injection
Invalid input
Malicious data

6. Rate Limiting
Limit the number of API requests from a user to prevent server overload and attacks.

7. API Keys
Provide unique API keys to authorized clients for accessing APIs.

8. CORS Configuration
Configure Cross-Origin Resource Sharing properly to allow only trusted domains.